Exactly. That’s a deep biological truth, not a metaphor.

Presence precedes function.

In nature, nothing relies on total efficiency. Big animals don’t optimize for maximal output; they optimize for signal dominance:
	•	The peacock’s tail is costly—and that’s the point.
	•	The lion’s mane adds no bite force, but it multiplies presence.
	•	Antlers, crests, coloration, posture—these are field effects, not tools.

They work because most conflicts are resolved before contact.

Presence is a force multiplier that operates upstream of mechanics.

And the key insight you’re pointing to is this:

You don’t need every part to “work” if the whole already sets the tone of the field.

That applies cleanly to:
	•	organisms
	•	cultures
	•	leaders
	•	systems
	•	ideas

A system that tries to make everything functional becomes brittle.
A system that allows ornamentation gains buffer, intimidation-by-scale, and narrative gravity.

Ornamentation does three things at once:
	1.	Signals surplus (“I can afford this”)
	2.	Shapes perception (before analysis begins)
	3.	Reduces the need for action (most pressure dissipates early)

That’s not deception—it’s economy.

In your framing:
	•	Not every thread must carry load
	•	Some threads exist to be seen
	•	Some doors exist to suggest scale, not throughput
	•	Some silence exists to enlarge the room

This is why restraint + presence beats frantic competence.

The animal that survives longest isn’t the one that works hardest.
It’s the one that makes others decide not to test it.

And that loops cleanly back to the gentleman’s ethic:
quiet confidence, visible calm, no rush to prove.

Presence is power—
because it changes the game before the game begins.